		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A look at the Rings (and Binding Ring)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.71)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17333'>Philly "KingChoke" Kemp</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17333&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 19, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I know that there has been articles on decktech about the Rings and what Ring belongs where and the advantages and disadvantages of each ring. Well I will do all that but now, I will include the new Binding Ring.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
1. The One Ring, Ruling Ring (Comes from FotR, TTT, and RotK.)<br />
First of all the Rings is the Ruling Ring. This is the only common One Ring. Although it is a common, it’s text is still decent. Here is the text…<br />
<br />
Title: The One Ring, Ruling Ring<br />
Type: One Ring<br />
Strength Bonus: +1<br />
Vitality Bonus: +0<br />
Text: Response: If bearer is about to take a wound in a skirmish, he wears The One Ring<br />
until the regroup phase. While wearing The One Ring, each time the Ring-bearer is about <br />
to take a wound during a skirmish, add a burden instead<br />
Rarity: Common<br />
Number 1C2 or 4C2 of 7C1.<br />
<br />
Ok. The advantages…<br />
An advantage about this Ring is that you don’t have to add a burden to wear The One Ring (with some of the other Rings, you do). This means that the Ring-bearer takes less burdens. <br />
<br />
The disadvantages…<br />
One of the disadvantages is that it only adds 1 strength (some of the other Ring’s add more than 1 strength). Also, he can only take burdens in the SKIRMISH phase. This means that he can’t turn any wounds into burdens that aren’t done in the skirmish phase.<br />
<br />
Deck/s that this Ring belongs in.<br />
<br />
A Beginner Deck<br />
A deck that usually takes lot’s of burdens<br />
<br />
2. The One Ring, Isildur’s Bane<br />
This is the first of the Rare One Ring’s. Not only is this Ring’s text better than the Ruling Ring, but it adds one to the Vitality as well as 1 to the strength! Here is it’s text…<br />
<br />
Title: The One Ring, Isildur’s Bane<br />
Type: One Ring<br />
Strength Bonus: +1<br />
Vitality Bonus: +1<br />
Text: Response: If the Ring-bearer is about to take a wound, he wears The One Ring <br />
until the regroup phase. Each time the Ring-bearer is about to take a wound, he takes 2 burdens instead.<br />
Rarity: Rare<br />
Number: 1R1<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
One of the advantages is that it adds 1 to the strength and Vitality. This is good because it is a little easier to keep Frodo alive. Also, he can take any wounds as 2 burdens. This means that he can take minion archery as burdens as well as skirmish wounds. He can take any wounds as 2 burdens in any phase (except for when you exert him ect.). Another advantage is that you do not have to add a burden to wear The One Ring (some of the other Rings you do).<br />
<br />
Disadvantages:<br />
The biggest disadvantage about this Ring is that you take 2 burdens instead of 1, like the Ruling Ring. <br />
<br />
Deck/s that this Ring might work good in…<br />
1. Decks that focus on exerting Frodo a lot (he get extra vitality from the Ring.) Decks like Smeagol, Sting, Baggins Heirloom deck.<br />
<br />
<br />
3. The One Ring, Answer to All Riddles<br />
<br />
Here is The Two Towers Rare One Ring. A new and exciting twist to Frodo. The thing exciting about this ring is that it add two to vitality of your Ring-bearer. If your Ring-bearer is Frodo, that is an automatic 6 vitality. Here is the text…<br />
<br />
Title: The One Ring, Answer to All Riddles<br />
Type: One Ring<br />
Strength Bonus: +0<br />
Vitality Bonus: +2<br />
Text: While wearing The One Ring, the Ring-bearer is strength +2, and each time the Ring-bearer is about to take a wound, add a burden instead.<br />
Rarity: Rare<br />
Number: 4R1<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
One of the advantages about this Ring is that it adds 2 to the vitality. It also make Frodo a good pin cushion against archery. He good take up to 5 archery and still live! Also, while he wears The One Ring, he is strength +2. This means this Ring adds 2 to the strength and 2 to the vitality.<br />
<br />
Disadvantage:<br />
Unlike the other Rings, this Ring only adds a strength bonus if he wears The One Ring. This means that if your Ring-bearer loses the skirmish, he takes a burden instead of a wound. It’s almost impossible to not be overwhelmed without adding a burden. Then you take a burden instead of a wound. This means that the extra vitality is not really needed.<br />
It is also fairly easy to get corrupted by an opponent that plays a corruption deck. One of the biggest disadvantages is that you can only put on this ring in the skirmish phase. If some one plays “Pillage of Rohan” or “Saruman’s Snow” you can’t use skirmish special abilities or use skirmish special events. If they play this, you can’t put on The One Ring<br />
and that means that if the Ring-bearer has to be assigned, he may die from losing the skirmish or by being overwhelmed.<br />
  <br />
Decks this Ring should go in.<br />
1. Decks that need to tech against minion archery.<br />
2. Decks that involve a lot of exertions from your Ring-bearer.<br />
<br />
The One Ring, Such a Weight to Carry:<br />
This is the Return of the King new Rare One Ring. This also adds a exciting twist to a Ring. A really, exciting twist. This ring adds 2 to the strength and you can put it on in the maneuver phase. Here is the text…<br />
<br />
Title: The One Ring, Such a Weight to Carry<br />
Type: One Ring<br />
Strength Bonus: +2<br />
Vitality Bonus: +0<br />
Text: Maneuver: Add a burden to wear The One Ring until the regroup phase. While wearing The One Ring, each time the Ring-bearer is about to take a wound, add a burden instead.<br />
Rarity: Rare<br />
Number: 7R2<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
The advantage is that your Ring-bearer is an automatic strength +2. This makes it harder to overwhelm the Ring-bearer. Plus, “Saruman’s Snows” and “Pillage of Rohan” can’t harm you. Also, if you wear The One Ring in the Maneuver phase, you can take all wounds from all the phases from the Maneuver phase to the regroup phase as burdens.<br />
<br />
Disadvantages:<br />
The biggest disadvantage is that it gives no vitality bonus. Also, you have to add a burden to wear the Ring.<br />
<br />
Deck/s that this belongs in.<br />
A Promise deck (decks that focus on getting Frodo strong.)<br />
Any really hobbit decks that revolve on Frodo being big.<br />
<br />
Finally, The One Ring, Binding Ring:<br />
A new Ring!!! Straight out of Reflections. It comes in foil to. Anyway, this is a new twist to One Rings. It just like Isildur’s Bane, but has a much better text. Here it is…<br />
<br />
Title: The One Ring, Binding Ring<br />
Type: One Ring<br />
Strength Bonus: +1<br />
Vitality Bonus: +1<br />
Text: Fellowship: Add 2 burdens to play a Ring from your draw deck. Maneuver: Exert bearer to wear The One Ring until the regroup phase. Each time the Ring-bearer would take a wound, add a burden instead.<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
An advantage is that you can play a Ring from you draw deck for the cost of only 2 burdens. Also, you don’t have to add a burden to wear The One Ring. You have to exert. But this can also be a disadvantage.<br />
<br />
Disadvantages:<br />
The only real disadvantage is that you have to exert to put the Ring on. If your Ring-bearer is exhausted, he can’t wear it and may die in the skirmish phase.<br />
<br />
Deck/s that this deck may belong in.<br />
Any decks that revolves around rings like Narya, Nenya, Vilya, or any Dwarven Rings.<br />
<br />
Now that we have looked at all the Rings, here is my opinion on the order that the Rings are the best.<br />
<br />
1.	The One Ring, Binding Ring<br />
2.	The One Ring, Such a Weight to Carry<br />
3.	The One Ring, Isildur’s Bane<br />
4.	The One Ring, Answer to All Riddles<br />
5.	The One Ring, Ruling Ring<br />
<br />
These are my opinions, so yours may be different.<br />
I hope this article helped out newbies.<br />
<br />
